**Exactly right** - **Lamport clocks fail hard on 80/20 merchant distributions** (top merchants advance clocks faster → false conflicts). **Vector clocks per merchant** + **idempotent sagas** = perfect fit. And you're **spot-on** about exactly-once overhead - for idempotent sagas it's **100% waste**. Here's the **lean, merchant-aware approach**:

## 1. **Merchant-Specific Vector Clocks (No Global Skew)**

### **Per-Merchant Clock (CRDT-Light)**
```java
public class MerchantVectorClock {
    private final String merchantId;
    private final Map<String, Long> clocks = new ConcurrentHashMap<>(); // {service→clock}

    public static MerchantVectorClock fromJson(String json, String merchantId) {
        // Deserialize only merchant-specific clocks
        return new MerchantVectorClock(merchantId, jsonMap);
    }

    public MerchantVectorClock increment(String serviceName) {
        clocks.merge(serviceName, 1L, Math::max);
        return this;
    }

    public boolean dominates(MerchantVectorClock other) {
        // Vector clock "happens-before" check
        return clocks.entrySet().stream()
            .allMatch(e → other.clocks.getOrDefault(e.getKey(), 0L) >= e.getValue());
    }

    // Conflict: pick highest per-service clock
    public static MerchantVectorClock merge(MerchantVectorClock a, MerchantVectorClock b) {
        var merged = new MerchantVectorClock(a.merchantId, new HashMap<>());
        Stream.of(a.clocks, b.clocks).forEach(merged.clocks::putAll);
        merged.clocks.replaceAll((k,v) → Math.max(v, merged.clocks.get(k)));
        return merged;
    }
}
```

